	  <title>Rotations are Distance Preserving</title>
	  <caption xmlns="">Rotations are Distance Preserving</caption>
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para xmlns="">
            <para.body>We say that a linear transformation <math>
                  <latex>L</latex>
               </math> preserves the distance between two points <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{a}</latex>
               </math>  and <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{b}</latex>
               </math> if the distance from <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{a}</latex>
               </math> to <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{b}</latex>
               </math> is equal to the distance from <math>
                  <latex>L(\Vect{a})</latex>
               </math> to <math>
                  <latex>L(\Vect{b})</latex>
               </math>. For example, a rotation of the plane about the origin preserves the distance between any two points.</para.body>
         </para>
			
			
			      <media xmlns="Theorem" type="image" active="0" inline="0">
            <img xmlns="" src="ims/RotationOrthogonal.png"/>
         </media>
			
		    </statement.showme>
	  </showme>
